:::summary
Augustine of Hippo (354–430 AD) was one of the most influential theologians and philosophers in Christian history. His writings on grace, original sin, and the nature of God shaped Western Christianity for over a thousand years. Though his conclusions differ significantly from Latter-day Saint theology, his intellectual rigor and spiritual journey remain a remarkable example of a mind wrestling with ultimate questions.
:::

